{{#extend "layout" title="Light Blue HTML5 Dashboard - Morris Charts"}}
{{#content "sidebar"}}
{{> sidebar active="charts_morris"}}
{{/content}}
{{#content "content" mode="replace"}}
<ol class="breadcrumb">
    <li class="breadcrumb-item">YOU ARE HERE</li>
    <li class="breadcrumb-item">Charts</li>
    <li class="breadcrumb-item active">Morris</li>
</ol>
<h1 class="page-title">Visual - <span class="fw-semi-bold">Chart</span></h1>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-lg-6">
        <section class="widget">
            <header>
                <h5>
                    Morris <span class="fw-semi-bold">Line Chart</span>
                </h5>
                <div class="widget-controls">
                    <a data-widgster="expand" title="Expand" href="#"><i class="la la-angle-up"></i></a>
                    <a data-widgster="collapse" title="Collapse" href="#"><i
                            class="la la-angle-down"></i></a>
                    <a href="#" data-widgster="close"><i class="la la-remove"></i></a>
                </div>
            </header>
            <div class="widget-body">
                <p class="fs-mini text-muted">
                    Good-looking charts shouldn't be difficult.
                    The public API is terribly simple. It's just one function: <code>Morris.Line(options)</code>,
                    where options is an object containing some of the following configuration options.
                </p>
                <div id="morris1" style="height: 343px">
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
    </div>
    <div class="col-lg-6">
        <section class="widget">
            <header>
                <h5>
                    Morris <span class="fw-semi-bold">Area Chart</span>
                </h5>
                <div class="widget-controls">
                    <a data-widgster="expand" title="Expand" href="#"><i class="la la-angle-up"></i></a>
                    <a data-widgster="collapse" title="Collapse" href="#"><i
                            class="la la-angle-down"></i></a>
                    <a href="#" data-widgster="close"><i class="la la-remove"></i></a>
                </div>
            </header>
            <div class="widget-body">
                <p class="fs-mini text-muted">
                    Good-looking charts shouldn't be difficult.
                    The public API is terribly simple. It's just one function: <code>Morris.Line(options)</code>,
                    where options is an object containing some of the following configuration options.
                </p>
                <div id="morris2" style="height: 343px">
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-lg-5 col-xl-5">
        <section class="widget">
            <header>
                <h5>
                    Morris <span class="fw-semi-bold">Bar Chart</span>
                </h5>
                <div class="widget-controls">
                    <a data-widgster="expand" title="Expand" href="#"><i class="la la-angle-up"></i></a>
                    <a data-widgster="collapse" title="Collapse" href="#"><i
                            class="la la-angle-down"></i></a>
                    <a href="#" data-widgster="close"><i class="la la-remove"></i></a>
                </div>
            </header>
            <div class="widget-body">
                <div id="morris4" style="height: 260px"></div>
                <p class="fs-mini text-muted">
                    Bar charts are also commonly referred to as a column charts. If you was trying to compare
                    the
                    height of something then intuitvely you would represent this by using columns.
                    This really couldn't be easier. Create a Bar chart using <code>Morris.Bar(options)</code>,
                    with only few options.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>
    </div>
    <div class="col-lg-3 col-xl-3">
        <section class="widget">
            <header>
                <h5>
                    Morris <span class="fw-semi-bold">Donut Chart</span>
                </h5>
                <div class="widget-controls">
                    <a data-widgster="expand" title="Expand" href="#"><i class="la la-angle-up"></i></a>
                    <a data-widgster="collapse" title="Collapse" href="#"><i
                            class="la la-angle-down"></i></a>
                    <a href="#" data-widgster="close"><i class="la la-remove"></i></a>
                </div>
            </header>
            <div class="widget-body">
                <div id="morris3" style="height: 180px">
                </div>
                <p class="fs-mini text-muted">
                    Donuts a great for representing some parted information like traffice sources,
                    disk partitions, etc.
                    This really couldn't be easier. Create a Donut chart using
                    <code>Morris.Donut(options)</code>,
                    with only few options.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>
    </div>
    <div class="col-lg-4 col-xl-4">
        <section class="widget">
            <header>
                <h5>
                    Morris <span class="fw-semi-bold">Bar Chart 2</span>
                </h5>
                <div class="widget-controls">
                    <a data-widgster="expand" title="Expand" href="#"><i class="la la-angle-up"></i></a>
                    <a data-widgster="collapse" title="Collapse" href="#"><i
                            class="la la-angle-down"></i></a>
                    <a href="#" data-widgster="close"><i class="la la-remove"></i></a>
                </div>
            </header>
            <div class="widget-body">
                <div id="morris6" style="height: 180px"></div>
                <p class="fs-mini text-muted">
                    This is generally a good chart to choose for all comparison based analysis but if you were
                    to display
                    a data set with negative values a column would be the best to represent this.
                    This really couldn't be easier. Create a Bar chart using <code>Morris.Bar(options)</code>,
                    with only few options.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>
    </div>
    <div class="col-lg-12">
        <section class="widget">
            <header>
                <h5>
                    Morris <span class="fw-semi-bold">Stacked Bar Chart</span>
                </h5>
                <div class="widget-controls">
                    <a data-widgster="expand" title="Expand" href="#"><i class="la la-angle-up"></i></a>
                    <a data-widgster="collapse" title="Collapse" href="#"><i
                            class="la la-angle-down"></i></a>
                    <a href="#" data-widgster="close"><i class="la la-remove"></i></a>
                </div>
            </header>
            <div class="widget-body">
                <div id="morris5" style="height: 200px">
                </div>
                <p class="fs-mini text-muted">
                    Stacked charts are excellent to track some dynamics within declared categories.
                    An example of this can be seen above.
                    To create a Stacked Bar chart use <code>Morris.Bar(options)</code> and set
                    <code>stacked</code>,
                    option to <code>true</code>.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>
    </div>

</div>
{{/content}}
